					</dt>
					<dd class="comment byuser comment-author-wbrounds bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-4605">
<p>Dave,</p>
<p>Good questions.  I think the nature of a typical hawala system prevent many of the problems you have mentioned.  Historically, hawala systems have an exceptionally low level of fraud.  Hawaladars trade in trust, their reputation in the community is what keeps them in business.  Barring any unusual circumstances, there si very little likelihood that they will sacrifice their reputation of trustworthiness.  I can foresee a possible issue when crossing ethnic or cultural barriers.  For example, a hawaladar might have no real negative consequences in his own community if he steals from someone from another ethnic or cultural community, but there is little evidence of that happening in the past.  </p>
<p>As far as recourse in court, an oral contract is just as valid as a written contract, it is just more difficult to prove the existence and terms of the contract.  Of course, where hawala is illegal, the contract will not be valid and so there will be no legal recourse.  Another potential issue is jurisdiction.  If you are remitting money from the one country to another, it will be hard to bring a non-performing party into court if they are in the other country.</p>
<p>Bill</p>
</div>
